				 Corporate taxes rise 41% in first half
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Oct. 4: Corporate taxes grew a record 41 per cent in the first half of 2007-08.																								Collections from companies stood at Rs 72,240 crore for the six months, April to September, against Rs 49,813 crore in the previous year. Advance tax payments increased 32 per cent during this period. 																								Public sector units are among the top advance-tax payers in the second quarter.																								The Oil and Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC), the largest PSU in the country, is believed to have paid Rs 2,401 crore as advance taxes in the second quarter, 17 per cent more than the corresponding period of the previous year.																								During this period, the State Bank of India paid Rs 1,051 crore, an increase of 22 per cent. Another PSU, Steel Authority of India Limited, paid Rs 900 crore, an increase of 20 per cent. Payments by the Life Insurance Corporation of India increased 14 per cent to Rs 731 crore.																								Among the power PSUs, payments by the National Thermal Power Corporation rose 17 per cent to Rs 526 crore.																								Bharat Heavy Electricals Limited paid Rs 470 crore, an increase of 34 per cent.																								Region-wise, the growth in the Bihar-Jharkhand circle was the highest at 265 per cent. It was 96 per cent in Mumbai and just 8 per cent in Delhi.																								In the first half, direct taxes, of which corporate taxes are a part, rose 40 per cent to Rs 1,11,055 crore. During this period, personal income tax increased 39 per cent and securities transaction tax, 48 per cent. Fringe benefit taxes grew by 103 per cent. 
